sed:\r\n is a windowing function. An example function, , is given in 17.3.2.5 (Mathematical \r\nconventions in the signal descriptions ).  is  for L-STF,  for L-LTF,  \r\nfor L-SIG,  for RL-SIG,  for U- SIG field,  for EHT-SIG,  for \r\nEHT-STF of EHT MU PPDU,  for EHT-STF of EHT TB PPDU,  for \r\nEHT-LTF, or  for EHT-Data.\r\n is defined in Table 36-23 (Frequently used parameters).\r\nFor pre-EHT modulated fields, . For EHT modulated fields,  \r\nfor an EHT MU PPDU, and  for an EHT TB PPDU, where  and \r\n are given in Table 36-23 (Frequently used parameters).\r\nis the power boost factor of the r-th occupied RU or MRU in an EHT MU PPDU and is \r\ndetermined by the POWER_BOOST_FACTOR parameter in the TXVECTOR. \r\nNOTE—  is set to the value of POWER_BOOST_FAC TOR in the TXVECTOR defined in 35.11.1.2 \r\n(POWER_BOOST_FACTOR).\r\nFor pre-EHT modulated fields,  is the set of subcarriers indices for all the tones in the \r\ncorresponding 20 MHz channels where EHT modulated fields are located for the r-th occupied \r\nRU or MRU. For EHT modulated fields in a nonpunctured non-OFDMA EHT PPDU that is \r\nnot in EHT DUP mode,  is the set of subcarriers indices from  to  as defined in \r\nTable 36-19 (Subcarrier allocation related cons tants for the EHT-modulated fields in a \r\nnonpunctured non-OFDMA EHT PPDU) excluding DC subcarriers. For EHT modulated fields \r\nin a nonpunctured non-OFDMA EHT MU PPDU transmitted in EHT DUP mode,  is the set \r\nof subcarriers indices for the tones in the r-th RU. For EHT modulated fields in a punctured\r\nnon-OFDMA EHT PPDU and an OFDMA EHT PPDU,  is the set of subcarriers indices for \r\nthe tones in the r-th RU or MRU. Data and pilot subcarrier indices for RUs are defined in \r\nrSubfield ru\r\niTX\r\nt\r\nrSubfield ru\r\niTX\r\nt wTSubfield\r\ntEr\r\nField\r\nNnorm r\r\n---------------------- KPre-EHT\r\n                            Qku>@ iTX m\r\nm 1=\r\nNSS r u\r\n¦\r\n Jk BW  Xkru\r\nm exp j2Sk'F Field tT GI Field TCS EHT Mru m+––\r